g.text: Door (Unopenable): An old door, worn by elements, guards the depot. The wind has blown a sand dune in front of it. The door hasn't been opened in a long while. You see a handle.
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant shrugs. "We don't get in there."
You: "Come on, we even got in the Light Bending Guy's container, but you're saying we can't get in here?"
You: "What do you mean? We get into... like... everywhere."
Kim Kitsuragi: "Relax. No one's hiding in there. If we can't open it, others can't either -- and thus they can't get in." He looks at the door with a rueful smile.
Conceptualization: At least you can *think* about opening it. About doors in general -- they are, after all, fundamental to your life. Perhaps something useful will come from this?
Door (Unopenable): There is no success. You didn't succeed here. It's impossible. The door does not open. It is not only locked, it is *jammed* shut.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Frankly, you're just going to have to accept the fact that you can't get in through every single door."
Door (Unopenable): You can't. This door cannot be opened...
Door (Unopenable): The concrete structure looks *military* in origin. Over half a century old at least, but sturdily built.
Rhetoric: No-no, we've gotten into every door thus far. That's what we do -- we open doors. We're cops, that's our perk. Even Evrart knew that's a part of our M.O.
You: "I'm not gonna accept this. The door could be part of the investigation."
You: "Could this structure have been used to take the shot?"
You: Huh... I wonder what's inside. How can I get in there?
"Huh, the door's shut tight. How can we get in there?"
You: What is this thing anyway?
Kim Kitsuragi: "Probably something that is no longer there." The lieutenant looks at the hunching, concrete toad in front of him.
"The washerwoman mentioned a depot up the coast." The lieutenant looks at the hunching, concrete toad in front of him. "She said it was for moving ammo and cargo across the bay -- this might be it"
Kim Kitsuragi: "It's military -- a service depot of some sort."
Rhetoric: No-no, we've absolutely gotten into everywhere thus far. That's what we do -- we open doors and go through them. We're cops, that's our perk.
Door (Unopenable): Yes. Better that way. You can't even fathom the rabbit hole you might find yourself in otherwise.
You: "But that's who I am. Who *we* are."
Visual Calculus: It may have been used to service an aerostatic battleship in the atmosphere? Or a fortification, like a seafort in the bay.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Yeah, I understand you, I like opening doors as much as the next guy, but this one is simply beyond repair and we don't have the resources needed to open it."
Kim Kitsuragi: "What else is there to do? *Not* accepting isn't gonna bring the fire brigade in..." He looks at the door with a rueful smile.
Conceptualization: At least you can *think* about opening it. About doors in general -- they are, after all, fundamental to your life. Perhaps something useful will come from this?
Visual Calculus: For servicing an aerostatic battleship in the atmosphere? Or a fortification, like a seafort in the bay?
Kim Kitsuragi: "From here to the Whirling? I can't see how..." He looks southeast and blows on his fingers: "The church is in the way."
Esprit de Corps: Relax, he thinks. There's no one in there. If we can't open it, neither can anyone else.
You: "Okay. I can live with this." (Accept it.)
Door (Unopenable): You rattle the handle a bit, then push on the door with all your weight -- it does not budge. Not only is it locked, it's also *jammed* shut.
